  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out right here in my shop in Naples. As a mechanic with three kids and a background in vocational training, I know that when people hear 'STEM' they often think of math and physics, not the practical, hands-on work we do every day. Stereotype threat happens when someone feels their identity is under threat because of a group label—like if a girl walks into a workshop and starts doubting herself because she's 'not good at math.' That anxiety can make her freeze, forget how to fix a car, or even quit before she even gets started. I've seen it in my own life too; my dad, who has a bachelor's degree, always told me I was 'too analytical' for a mechanic, but that's not true. It's about how we're taught to see ourselves. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with lectures or big campaigns that don't connect to real life. In my shop, we talk about fixing things together, not about numbers. We play board games with the kids to build problem-solving skills, and I make sure they know that being good at fixing things isn't about being 'smart' in a textbook way—it's about patience and hands-on experience. The key is to create spaces where people feel safe to try, fail, and learn without judgment. For me, that means starting with small, everyday tasks—like helping my kids with their homework or fixing a leaky faucet—so they see that learning is part of life, not a competition. If we can make STEM feel accessible and relatable, not intimidating, then we're not just fixing cars, we're building confidence in everyone.",
